    "title": "SDRF-Proteomics: Affinity Proteomics Template",
    "content": "SDRF-Proteomics: Affinity Proteomics Template\n\n//only works on some backends, not HTML\n\n//use style like Section 1 when referencing within the document.\n\n//GitHub specific settings\n\nStatus of this Template\n\nThis document provides guidelines for annotating affinity-based proteomics experiments in SDRF-Proteomics format. This template extends the core SDRF-Proteomics specification with affinity proteomics-specific metadata fields.\n\nVersion 1.0.0 - 2025-01\n\nAbstract\n\nAffinity proteomics encompasses experimental approaches that use affinity-based capture methods to study specific protein subsets or interactions. Unlike mass spectrometry-based proteomics, these methods typically use antibodies, aptamers, or other affinity reagents to detect and quantify proteins. Major platforms include:\n\n- Proximity Extension Assay (PEA): Olink platform using antibody pairs and DNA barcoding\n- Aptamer-based assays: SomaScan platform using modified aptamers (SOMAmer reagents)\n- Antibody arrays: Various bead-based and planar array platforms\n- Immunoaffinity-MS: Hybrid approaches combining affinity capture with MS detection\n\nThis template defines metadata requirements for annotating these diverse affinity-based proteomics experiments, enabling data integration across platforms and with mass spectrometry data.\n\nMotivation\n\nAffinity proteomics experiments have characteristics that differ significantly from mass spectrometry proteomics:\n\n1. Pre-defined protein panels: Target proteins are determined by the reagent panel, not by detection\n2. No mass spectrometry (typically): Detection is often via sequencing, fluorescence, or electrochemiluminescence\n3. High throughput: Many samples can be processed in parallel\n4. Different quantification scales: Relative units (NPX, RFU) rather than intensity or spectral counts\n5. Platform-specific considerations: Each technology has unique metadata requirements\n\nThese aspects require specific metadata to enable proper data interpretation and cross-platform co",
