    "title": "SDRF-Proteomics: Cell Line Template",
    "content": "SDRF-Proteomics: Cell Line Template\n\n//only works on some backends, not HTML\n\n//use style like Section 1 when referencing within the document.\n\n//GitHub specific settings\n\nStatus of this Template\n\nThis document provides guidelines for annotating cell line-based proteomics experiments in SDRF-Proteomics format. This template extends the core SDRF-Proteomics specification with cell line-specific metadata fields and resources.\n\nVersion 1.0.0 - 2025-01\n\nAbstract\n\nCell lines are extensively used in proteomics research, both for biological studies and for technology/method development. Cell lines present unique annotation challenges because:\n\n- They have well-defined characteristics that can be retrieved from databases\n- Metadata like sex, age, and disease refer to the original donor, not the cell line passage\n- Multiple databases and ontologies exist for cell line identification\n- Cell lines may be misidentified, contaminated, or have undergone genetic drift\n\nThis template defines standardized approaches for annotating cell line experiments, including the use of Cellosaurus as the primary resource for cell line identification and metadata.\n\nMotivation\n\nCell line annotation in proteomics datasets has historically been inconsistent:\n\n1. Multiple naming conventions: HeLa, HELA, He-La may all refer to the same cell line\n2. Outdated ontologies: The Cell Line Ontology (CLO) has not been actively maintained\n3. Missing metadata: Key information about donor characteristics is often omitted\n4. No standard identifiers: Lack of consistent accession numbers for cell lines\n\nThis template addresses these issues by:\n\n- Recommending Cellosaurus as the primary cell line resource\n- Providing a curated database of cell line metadata for SDRF annotation\n- Defining which metadata fields should be populated from databases vs. experiment-specific annotation\n\nCellosaurus: The Primary Cell Line Resource\n\nCellosaurus is a comprehensive knowledge resource on cell lines maintained by the SIB Swiss I",
